{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_ekiden_ver02/data/sn83016804/00393340563/1958041101/0895.xml":{"full_text":"ST. PAUL RECORDER\n\"An Independent Newspaper\"\nE.takll.hM) Aufu.t I*. IM4. kT Cell E. Kinw\nr iMiihim 1\n1,\nlie IS. Minnesota.\nMMKdim 4th t.VUf lU fit Fm\nUi Third jy\u00bbn\u2014 joitli, Mina*\n\u25a0U\u2014g'W\u00df _ _\nCApital 2-o\u2018>22 I'IIONES FEilenil .'<-707,\nKntara.l ttri.nll'Cltu mattar Juna 14. !*1\u00bb. at Ih. poit offlca mi SI\nPaul. Mlnnaaota. undar Ih* Act of March I. II7\u00bb Postmaster. |>laaaa\nforward form 1471 to >4l Third Aaa. So, Mlnnaapolia It. Mlnnaaota\nNf Hat HIPTfO.N KATKR\nMlnnaaota. North and Ilouth Dakota, ona jraat |i 00, ala months 11.00\nAll olhar atataa >4 00 par roar; ala montha, |4 00 All mall aabscrlptlons\npayahls strictly In ad Vanda.\nC.cll K N.wman 7.777777:...... 7 Editor l-uhllahar\nCurt la C. Cblvars\nDa VaJma Nawmaa bookkaaplna\nNall Dodaon Ituaaail Cootrlbutlna Editor\nJaaala Shspard Social A Paraonwl Nawa\nCheater W Pattaraon AdTartlaln*\nLaalaa Hushas\nVara M. Larson Production\niloui Valla. South Dakota Coirespondent. Mrs Dan doataa. \u00bb10 North\nMahla. dloua Kalla. South Dakota.\nWaal Cnael Itapi aaanlat l> Hobart Whale> 700 Mont\u00abornery\nSt_, San Franclaco I. Calif. Talaphona slitter l\u00abo7> Im Anaalaa Offlca\ntill lloiljrwood Boulevard, Phona HOllrwood I 7117\nNational Advartlalna llapraaantatlvaa: ASSOCIATED PI'HLISHKIIA. Inc.\nII Want 4\u00abth St.. Naw Turk I*. N. Y\u2014Chicago Offlca: 1\u00ab# W. Wa.hlna\ntdSb OBasao I. Illinois.\nThl. nawapapar mumu no raap'.nalblh! y tor unsolleftad manuacrlpta,\nphotos or anffravlriffs Much srs aubmlftad at nwnar\u2019e rtah _____\nMraikan Natlaaal BJlfarlal Aa*<i\u00abfallM\nNaakan NlaatMia BlltaHal iMMlatln\nMaaiban Natlaaal Nawapapar Pvbllahrra Aaaarlallaa\nNawa Barvlraa Aaaoclatad Na*ro Pr-aa. Conllaantal raaturaa and\nNawapraaa Photos\nThe RECORDER believes no nun should be denied the right to\ncontribute his beet to humanity. Ae long es that right le denied any\nman. no man's rights are safe.\nFRIDAY, APRIL 11, I\u00aes\u00df\nG.O.P. (lampuigri Strategy Takes Shape\nNorthern Republicans hsve a top-drawer plan to closely Identify\nnorthern Democrat* with the southern Democrat* In the coming con\ngressional campaign In another attempt to wenn the numerous north\nern Negro voters sway from Democratic rank*.\nSo far thl* strategy ha* not worked but Negro Democrat* and\nthe Independent Negro voter* are admittedly restive under southern\ndomination of the party In Congress ns represented by the Sam\nRayburns and the Lyndon Johnson*, where the more liberal northern\nDemocratic Congressmen and Henatnra allow the \"tall to wag the\ndog.\"\nRepublican* however have a Job answering the truth that for\nyears the federal civil right* legislation wa* stopped by an unholy\nalliance between northern Republican* In the Senate especially, and\nthe southern Ivmocrat*. whom for present political strategy they are\nsupposed to despise.\nThe shape of the strategy-to-coine could bo seen In John Culver's\n\"Letters to the Editor,\" on this page for the past six month* wherein\nJohn tries to prove that Hubert Humphrey and Minnesota Democrat*\nsuch as Orville Freeman are responsible for the presence In the\nCongress of Individuals like James Eastland and Htrom Thurmond! Of\ncourse Mr. Culver and his OOP-line have never mentioned a Minne\nsota Congressman like John O' Hara who ha* voted with the Dlxle\ncrats In every civil rights battle In Congress except the most recent one\nor a Republican. Senator* like Karl Mundt of South Dakota or Young\nof North Dakota who are no better on civil rights Issues than the worse\nsouthern Democrat*.\nEditorial !Nol\u00ab*h\nThe U.B I* now safe for America First, now that Ed Viehman\nha* took out after Harry Truman and Hubert Humphrey!\nMeade Alcorn. Republican National Committee chairman said\na mouthful when he asserted In a speech Monday night the Senator\nJohn Kennedy ha* had a very unsatisfactory record since the Presi\ndential bug hit him. Kennedy has flipped and flopped all over the\nlot since the 1I\u00bbM convention when he almost won the Vice-Presi\ndential assignment from the Democrat* chiefly through the efforts\nof conservative southern f\u00bbemorrata. Since that time he has flipped\nand flopped around on such Issues as civil right* to add to hi* earlier\nunsatisfactory votes on lha farm tsauue.\nThe Presidential bug makes some very unsatisfactory mealy\nmouthed characters out of some formerly forthright statesmen.\n\nPolitical leaders among Bt. Paul's Negro population are strange\nly silent about the current city elections Is everybody satisfied?\ne e e\nPresident Elsenhower seems more concerned about \"private enter\nprise,\" than he Is about the things which mnke \"private enterprise\u2019\u2019\nclick such as Jobs and economic stability. If we don't plan and work\nour way out the current recession there may not be any \"private en\nterprise\" to protect.\nDoes anyone ever remember seeing any Negro talent on either\nthe Hob Hope show or the Dinah Shore, Chevrolet T V. shows?\n\nPaul Butler the Democratic National chairman also uttered\na realistic mouthful when he said Monday In a speech \"The big Issue\nfacing the American people today la Job* not political gains next\nNovember. We cannot afford to wait and see millions of American\nmen and women out of work and do nothing about It.\" Amen Brother\nButler.\n\nWe are agin any political party playing politic* with the current\nrecession. The one which does ought to receive a resounding licking\nfrom the electorate.\n\nIt's probably unpopular to suggest but It seems to this news\npaper that educational Institutions at the elementary and high school\nlevel* ought to remain open 12 months a year Thl* might ease the\nterrific and growing pupil load and the Inadequate facUHtlaa\n\nWe\u2019re In complete sympathy with the fellow who suggests that\nwe spend some of the brains and energy we are using on plans to\nreach the moon on finding some way to keep peace and pro*|>ertty on\nthe earth!\nNotice: The F.a*ter Parade was postponed to Sunday April 13 by\norder of the Snow King\u2019\nIf you want a preliminary Easter Parade It will be found at the\n28th annual 8t Thomas Episcopal Church Style Show at the lemn\ntngton Hotel, tonight Friday April II\nWhen two buildings occupied by Jewish synagogue activity were\ndynamited In Florida and Tennessee this newspaper ex per'test great\nindignation to be expressed by the leading Christian denominations\nbut instead the alienee was oppressive\nWe have not seen In the press a denunciation of such bar Iran sill\nby a single outstanding clergyman or laymen of the Christian faith\nThis to us is aa shameful as the bombings.\nDougin* Dayton, Not Minneapolis\nUrban League President\nThe Minneapolis l T rban I-eagtie is to be congratulated on the\nelection of Douglas Dayton as preaidant last week Mr Dayton's\nelection follows the pattern set by the league tn attracting to it* top\nposition men of worth, service and distinction in the community This\nhappy circumstance In part accounts in a large measure for the con\ntinued success and preatige of the program of this Important Bed\nFeather agency.\nHaving watched the Interest exhibited by Mr Dayton, since\nhi* election to the I\u2019rban League board several vears ago. this news\npaper la extremely happy that the league board recognised that in\nterest. and named him to the presidency\nThe League has many Important tasks before It and with such\nleadership as Mr Dayton can offer, especially. ,t the time when there\nU to be a change in the executive director, It la indeed fortunate in Ita\nselection of a president.\nEditor\u2019s Note: The editorial reprinted above from m .r April 4\nedition had the wrong title on It la that law. The sohjorl of the\npiece was Douglas J. Dayton but the title road \"Donald\" Dayton\nwho Is of course a well known brother of our editorial .object\nMuch error, occur we hasten to rationalise. the heat new .paper\nahopa. sad the beet we can do la correct u\u00bbe mistake Moot of\nace proud of our own name and don\u2019t waal to he railed by another\n'hence, are lha,\nenr renders noticed the error but we did and It sturk out to u\u00bb\nUkr a sore thumb\nE'M PAKIH&CCOU&; TOWy'KiDsA\nwhyponyYoomvire\nVoofL p&ehps ovi^J\u00dfk\n'akc Ari Interest In Your Kids Friends. They Will Be Happi\nAt Home\nLetters To The Editor\nNothing Wrong That Buying Won't Cur*\nEditor; Nothing I* wrong with hi Hum-Ha today except that Mr\nand Mr*. Public are not buying the thinga that they want, need\nand can afford to buy.\nIf our advertiaing medium* hope to continue to aell advertising\nIt I* up to them to convince the public that it U their purrjiuae* that\nwill put men back to work.\nWhy not an advertising campaign In the papers, on the Radio and\nT V. picturing It as a patriotic duty for every one to BUY NOW.\nSincerely, 1.. A. Stone. 4131 Portland Ave. So., Minneapolis, March\n31, 111.13.\nGot Thm Democrats Toot Oft Our Brothers' s Neck/\nEditor: The more than 2.000 Negroe* who assembled on the steps\nof Alabama's State Capitol and Joined with the Rev. Martin Luther\nKing, Jr.; i Montgomery Buss boycott leader! to protest the mis\ncarriage of Justice In the courts that led to the legal lynching of\nJeremiah Reeve*. Jr.; should be a grim reminder of things to come,\nIf we continue to supply the vote that untimately puts Southern\nDemocrats in power.\nThe mob. which in years gone by would string its vlctoms to the\nnearest tree nr tie a hapless Negro to the stake for a public burning.\nI* now obsolete thanks to years of effort by the National Association j\nfor the Advancement of Colored People (NAACPI.\nBut Alabama has out-lawed the NAACP. During the 1956 elec\ntion campaign. I predicted, that should the Democrats win that could\nwell be the beginning of the end of the one organization that has\nconsistently fought for the rights of the Negro.\nNorth Carolina was the only Southern state during 1957, where\nthe membership of the NAACP did not fall off, according to the re\nports of the delegates to the sixth annual regional NAACP con-'\nventlon held at Greensboro, N.C.\nMiss Ruby Hurley, Southeastern NAACP Regional Secretary said\nstate probes had reduced membership In Florida, Georgia, South\nCarolina and Tennessee and that branches tn Mississippi were \"under\nthe hammer of fear\u201d from White Citizens Councils\nWe remember Sen. James O. Eastland (D. Miss. I speaking before\nthe White Citizens Council at Senatobia. Mississippi on or about Aug\nust 12. 1954 and telling them not to obey the U. S. Supreme Court*\nruling on segregation.\nSen Eastland was Chairman of the powerful Judiciary Com\nmittee. When he speaks. Southerners listen. His committee has to\napprove Federal Judge Appointments, and the Senator never misses\nan opportunity to quiz the prospective Judge about hi* views on Civil\nRights.\nIt\u2019s Senator Eastland's Committee that has held up President\nElsenhower's appointment of Mr. Tiffany as Staff Director of the!\nCivil Rights Commission and therefore Mr Tiffany could not select\nthe members of his staff.\nSenator Eastland, like Senator John McClellan (D. Ark.i hold\nChairmanships ol powerful committees and their foot on the Negroe*\nnack.\nMississippi Democrat officials threatened Army Sgt. John Wheeler\nwith 10 years In prison for bringing his German bride to his home town\nlaurel. Mississippi Apparently Sen McClellan with other Southern\ners, wanted the same provision extended to Army Campa in the South\nThose of us who came from the South, know that the Southern\nDemocrat* put laws prohibiting Negroes and white* from marrying,\nso they said but we know that those laws were put there, to prevent\nthe Negro mother from compelling the white father to give anything\nto support his child.\nArrington High. Mississippi Negro editor, escaped alive In a\nwooden coffin because he dared to name 143 white men tn his county\nwho were father* of \"Negro\" children\nThose of us that came from the South know the conditions that\nexist there *o let us remember that when we vide for a Democrat here\nin the North that vote aids in putting anti-Negro polltleans in charge\nof vital committees where they can aid the White Citizens Councils and\nthe Ku Ktux Klan in oppressing the Negroes that dare to live in (he\n8011th.\nRemember how we fared in the South when we vote' sincerely,\nJohn M. Culver, Chairman Ramsey County Republican Civil Right*\ncommittee, .135 Kndlcott-on Robert. April 3, 1953.\nHappiness Her Summer Target!\n'Greatest Problem' Stirs South\nWe think it I* sheer irresponsibility when men suggest that we\njunk the public school system of North Carolina in order to prevent\n1 integration of the races in classrooms!\nExtremists on either side of this controversy will do severe ajvl\nlireparable damage to the state of North Carolina and to the people\nof this state It is not a time for haste nor exaggeration. It is a time for\nserious consideration and deliberation.\nEssentially, the question is this: Will the whites accept the decis\nion of the United States Supreme Court and allow their children to\nattend school with Negro children; or: Will the Negroes acquiesce and\nthereby be denied in their efforts to enter the heretofore white\nschools\nIt cannot be denied that the Negroes have the Supreme Court of\nthe United States on their side. They also have the beliefs of many\nthat all taxpaying citizens of the United States are entitled to access\nto public Institutions without discrimination because of color.\nIn vew of the two questions listed above, it is obvious that one\nside or the other will be forced to give ground. There must be either\nsegregation or integration! The white citizns must either allow in\ntegration or else the Negroes must accept segregation!\nExtremists on the pro-segregation side would defy the laws of\nthe land and take any measure in order to preserve segregation. They\nwould Junk the public school system and make it necessary for all\npeople to pay tuition fees for the education of their children. They\nwould In thetr ill advised haste put an end to the state supported\nschool system and leave it to a \"grab bag\" system of obtaining an\neducation.\nThe question now seems to be: How and when can compliance\nbe realized to the mutual agreement and harmonious acceptance of\nboth sides?\nTherein lies the greatest problem Southern society has ever faced.\nSuch a problem deserves and requires the prayerful study and de\nliberation of every Southerner and every American everywhere!\u2014\nThe Cleveland (Shelby. N.C.) Time*.\nHow To Stop Mud-Slinging\nNext year a Republican and a Democrat will seek the presidency\nWouldn't it be wonderful if the campaign could be conducted with a\nminimum of personal attacks with an emphasis on the issues rather\nthan on personalities?\nThose who deplore mud slinging politics all too often put the blame\non professional politicians. It is true that some politicians resort to this\nkind of electioneering but if they do it is because they have found it to\nbe politically profitable. If there were not weak, mentally-sick people\nready to buy dope there would be no dope peddlers; if there were\nnot a sizable body of voters willing to listen to the villfier and the\nslanderer these unwholesome types would vanish from the political\nscene.\nCandidates for the presidency are sometimes goaded into intem\nperate remarks and sometimes even fall from the high plane of their\nown accord. But for the most part they view gutter politics with the\ndistaste that might be expected from men who seek such a responsible\nposition.\nGood citizens can raise the level of campaigns by letting political\nleaders, even those they favor, know that any appeal aimed at arousing\nthe worst instincts of voters will be rejected. Bremer County In\ndependent, Wuverly, In.\nHR WATCH\nHa, POTOMAC\nBy ROBERT G. SPIVACK\nWashington Win DO I\u2019KICES STAY UP?\u2014The parado:\niif the 1958 recession is easily stated, but not so readily under\nitood and it\u2019s beginning to worry a lot of people. The econom;\nis in the midst of what TIME magazine ealls a \u201cpause fo\nbreath\u201d. If what we learned in college economics were tru\nprices should he tumbling.\nThe essence of the \u201cfree e\nwas this. If the demand falls off\nthe seller lowers his price. When\nthe price becomes attractive\nenough for the buyer he will take\nthe product off the seller's hands.\nBut it isn't working that way.\nTake the case of oil and gasoline.\nThere is so much oil now in the\nU. S. we don't know what to do\nwith It. According to reliable re\nports from Texas there are ex\ncess stocks of 781,000,000 barrels.\nDo the Big Oil interests let\nth\u00ab public in on this secret You\ncan be darned sure of the answer\nand it's \"no\". Instead the Texas\noilmen send up a hue and cry\nabout \"foreign\" imports. Venezu\nela, which is virtually a colony of\nStandard Oil of New Jersey, is\nforced to cut back on her pro\nduction Other small oil-producing\nnations face the same situation.\nCanadian oil sales are in bad\nshape.\nThe main drive of the Big Oil\ninterests the little oilman simply\nhas nothing to say about it\u2014la\nto keep prices high. In many\nEastern states a gallon of gasoline\nsells for anywhere from 32c to i\n39c depending on whether it Is\n\"high test.\" or regular' or super\nduper high octane. Result: many\nordinary people who used to go\nriding on the week-ends for plea\nsure now stay home and watch\ntelevision. It's not only cheaper;\nit's more convenient.\nThere la a further result: tire\ndealers can't sell their products.\nGeneral Tire Co. has even sanc\ntioned announcements on radio\nthat its dealers are overstocked.\nYet tire manufacturers aren't of\nfering any bargains.\nWHO GETS IT IN THE NECK\nThe question of rutting prices\nresolve* itself simply into this\nwho is going to take the inevitable\nfinancial beating that must come\nwith price reductions? If the re\ntailer cuts prices while he is over\nstocked. he is the profits loser\nIf the wholesaler does the rutting\nwhile the stock is on his hands\nhe must bear the burden of a\nprofit s reduction.\nThe only solution that Big Bus\niness has come up with so far is\nto let the laboring men take the\nbeating He's simply fired and that\nBEST NATIONAL AND LOCAL PICTURE\nCOVERAGE OF ANY PAPER OF ITS SIZE\nIN THIS AREA\nREADERS ALWAYS KNOW WHERE THIS\nPAPER STANDS EDITORIALLY ON\nIMPORTANT ISSUES\nKsonomy\u201d as we were taught it\nremoves a high coat from the in\ndustrialist\u2019s budget. But there are\nother things that result from mass\nlay-offs.\nIf a workingman cannot buy\nthen the retailer can't unload his\natock. If he can't get rid of what\nts on his shelves then he'll certain\nly not take off the wholesaler's\nhands the inventories he is carry\ning. And then we get back to the\nIndustrialist who isn't producing\nor selling. That's how a downward\nspiral makes a little recession into\na big depression.\nThe crisis that we are suffering\nis essentially a crisis of confidence\nnot simply one of profits.\nThe big bankers who control\ncredit won't release it until they\nknow what their cut (interest)\nis to be and what plans, if any.\nthe government has for stimulat\ning new production.\nThus far we have had two anti\nrecession measures: a big housing\nbill and a II 1 billion increase for\ndefense spending. The latter, of\ncourse, is sheer waste. For unex\nj plained reasons the Administra\ntion would rather build arms and\nlet them rust than help small un\ndeveloped countries get on their\nI feet.\nReports coming to the office of\nVice President Nixon are that the\npublic is growing a little tired of\nall this indecision by federal of\nficials. A \"little recession' may be\ngood for some people: It's ob\ni vtouaty quite good for the big\nommervial banks. They have\nmade a killing on the juggling of\ninterest rates.\nBut it's no good for ordinary\npeople and it's no good for Re\npublican politicians. Even Detn\noerstm run a risk when things\nstay bad too long. People get\nrestise and begin to talk of \"throw\ning the rascals out\" without re\ngsrd to party label\n\nRECESSION NOTE A broken\ndown old car pulled up to the toll\ngate at the Lincoln Tunnel, re\nports former Congressman T\nJames Tumulty.\n\"Fifty cents,'' said the collector\n\u201cSold.\" replied the driver.\n(Copyright 19*8. Robert O\nSplvack).\nPage 2, St Paul RECORDER, Friday. April 11. 1968\nThe reward* offered by s career as an editor or publisher of a\nNegro newspaper sie often more Intellectual and spiritual than\nIn an article in the anniversary edition of the Louisville DE\nFENDER writer Nat Tillman teila aomething of the trials and\ntribulations of Editor Frank Stanley, which In a measure have been\nshared or duplicated in the career* of moat Negro editors and pub\nlishers in the field whether (hey serve large or small constituencies.\nWrote Tillman\nEditor Stanley Interrupted hi* dinner recently to come to the\ntelephone The caller waa crying and appealing for someone to stop the\nBoard of Education from closing Lincoln School. Calls of all sorts at\nall hour* com* to the Stanley residence. \"Can I get a photographer?\nWill you send a reporter? We want you to speak at our church.\" Also\nthere are calls to disagree with or complain about a story in the\nDefender But telephone calls sre not the only bother of a Negro\nnewspaper publisher.\nPhysical Threats\nHe must withstand physical threats, arrests, financial pinches,\nparticipate In every worthwhile movement and give leadership to all\ngood causes. In the main he must of necessity run the risk of being\nunpopular\u2014because the complacent, the afraid and the prejdiced are\never his critics.\nNot only must he print the news but he must roll up his sleeves\nand lead the fight for first class citizenship. Those who disagree will\ncall him an agitator. Those who agree will take It for granted that he\nIs obligated to crusade\u2014hence he deserves no special thanks.\nOf Common Clay\nThe average white publisher is a person of limited contact with\nhis readership. He first of all is usually very wealthy, lives on an\nexclusive estate and socializes mostly in private clubs. The Negro\npublisher is known intimately by most of his readers\u2014he lives in\nthe same type of neighborhood, belongs to the same social organiza\ntions and sweats out an existence like any other Negro. He enjoys no\nivory tower. So when he crusades for advancement, he does so both out\nof selfish interest and a spirit of service.\nEditor Stanley, for example, was escorted by two detectives during\nthe 1937 flood to Mayor Neville Miller's office because the Defender\ncriticized the mayor for discrimination of flood victims. Mayor Miller\nannounced to Stanley that he was going \"to run you out of town if\nyou don't retract.\" Stanley didn't retract nor leave town.\nWhen the Defender bought a building in downtown Louisville the\nColumbians threatened to blow it up. The Defender remained in this\nproperty twelve years without losing an hour of work.\nSearch for Truth\nBefore the last public hanging in Owensboro. Kentucky. Stanley.\nAttorney R Everett Ray and reporter Frank Gray went to Owensboro\nIn the interest of a new trial for the accused rapist. When they sought\ncourt records, they were told to get out of town or else. They stayed an\nentire day and got enough information to file an appeal in federal\nEditor Stanley voluntarily assumed the responsibility of raising\nfunds to sue the University of Louisville. The suit was not necessary\nand the *1,500 raised was given to the NAACP. A more recent project\ncarried on by the publisher of the Louisville Defender was the aid given\nthe Gordons of Clay. With more than S4OO raised by the paper, the\nGordons were able to relocate in another state away from facial strife.\nThrough the years he has spearhead many charities.\nPark Opened\nBefore any city park was reopened to Negroes, Stanley led a\ndelegation to Mayor Farnsley's office and succeeded in desegregating\nElliot Park at 28th and Elliot. After Mayor Famsley relented, Stanley,\nhis two sons, and Mark Anthony were the first to enter the park. They\nwere met by some twenty white children who questioned their presence.\nThere was no disturbance but an hour later upon leaving Elliott Park,\nthe foursome was met by police officers who threatened to arrest them\nfor trespassing.\nSome Rewards\nHowever, the hard work is not without its rewards Publisher\nStanley felt honored when he was chosen as the first Negro to head\nan overseas commission to investigate the conditions faced by troops\nin Europe. He knew that it was his militancy and crusading that\nearned him the post.\nStanley, like most of the editors 1 know, or have learned about,\ncould find a whole lot of easier ways to earn a respectable living\nbut he love* the challenge, the opportunities and the service potential\nof publishing a class newspaper.\nHis greatest reward for 16 and 18 hour days, brick bats and ex\nisting economy lay in. he believes, the fact that he is making a con\ntribution that the NAACP, the Urban League, the white press, can't\nmake In fact. It is a contribution that ONLY a \"cause\" newspaper\nwith a dedicated editor could make.\nHe has no thoughts of giving up in the foreseeable future because\nthe road to complete freedom is rough, slippery and longer that many\npeople realize So Frank L. Stanley, like all the great editors whose\nlegacy he holds, will be trodding uphill until. I'm sure, victory is won.\nNat Tillman wrote a nice piece about his chief. To a great extent\nas we wrote iq the first paragraph Stanley's experience as a newsman\napproximates that of many other Negro editors and publishers in these\nUnited Sttes. Cecil Newman.\nGET WHAT YOU WANT AND SAVE TIME\nMONEY AND ENERGY WITH HELPFUL\nWANT ADS IN THIS PAPER\nf- \u2014v\nwhy HUtl fir the phone?\nreach fo-a,/\nJ#*\nNO MORE RUSHING to answer a distant ring\nwhen vou have a telephone in your haaement\nworkshop And it's just the place for one of\nthe new space-savin* phone* that mount\nhandily on the wall.\nWTiy not call your Telephone Business\nOffice right away and see how little it costa\nto have this modem convenience in your\nhome Sonhurattm Ml Ttlephon* Company","height":"20811","width":"15729"}}
